Friday. Then she proved why she was the Big Ten's player of the

article.headline: Mazzante on the money down the stretch
article.linkText: Penn State survives close call against Indiana
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Kelly Mazzante struggled for 39 minutes
Friday. Then she proved why she was the Big Ten's player of the
year.

	   Mazzante grabbed a key rebound, hit an off-balance 3-pointer and
made two free throws in the final 66 seconds Friday to help 
Penn State (No. 15 ESPN/USA Today, No. 14 AP) avoid an upset with a 67-64 victory over defending Big
Ten Conference tournament champion Indiana.

	   "I knew I hadn't made too many,'' Mazzante said of the
3-pointer that gave Penn State a four-point lead with 49 seconds
left. "But in a situation like that, my teammates needed me to
make that shot.''

	   Penn State (24-7) will meet Ohio State, a 71-55 winner over
Michigan State on Friday, in the first semifinal Sunday.

	   Getting there, though, was difficult.

	   For Mazzante, the conference scoring champ at 24.5 points per
game, it was an atypical game by any of her standards.

	   She struggled to get shots off against the Hoosiers' pesky
defense, taking only six in the first half. Her first basket didn't
come until 18:41 into the game and that was on a layup.

	   Frustrated in the second half, she began forcing shots, and
although she finished with 18 points, half came on free throws.

	   But after Tanisha Wright fouled out with 1:31 to go and with the
Nittany Lions in a 61-61 tie, Mazzante took control.

	   Mazzante wasn't the only one having problems Friday.

	   Wright was the only consistent scorer for Penn State, the
conference regular-season champs and tournament's top seed. She hit
8-of-11 shots and had a team-high 26 points.

	   The rest of the team combined to make only 12-of-44, including
Mazzante's 4-of-14 effort, and the taller Nittany Lions also were
outrebounded by Indiana (13-15) 38-30.

	   "It's embarrassing we didn't rebound much better than that,''
Penn State coach Rene Portland said. "I thought we looked tired.''

	   The game had a similar feel to last year's title game in which
the Hoosiers upset Penn State 75-72 to win their first conference
tournament title.

	   The Hoosiers stayed close throughout, allowing Penn State to
lead by no more than five. Twice in the second half, Penn State
went on 8-2 runs and both times the Hoosiers countered with 7-0
runs.

	   "Turnovers down the stretch hurt us,'' said Indiana coach Kathi
Bennett, whose tournament record dropped to 5-2. "That's something
we've tried to tried to address. That's huge.''

	   Still, the eighth-seeded Hoosiers played well enough to give
themselves a chance.

	   They led 61-59 when Lisa Eckart made a spinning layup with 3:24
remaining. Eckart finished with 15 points but only managed two in
the second half.

	   Wright's steal and uncontested layup with 2:40 left tied the
score.

	   Kristen Bodine, who hit the game-winner for Indiana with 9.8
seconds left Thursday, then missed two free throws and when Penn
State's Jennifer Brenden made 1-of-2 free throws, Mazzante came up
big.

	   She rebounded Brenden's miss, called time-out and then hit an
off-balance 3-pointer from the left wing to give the Nittany Lions
a 65-61 lead.

	   Indiana got a three-point play from Cindy Valentin and Mazzante
hit two free throws to make it 67-64 with 19.1 seconds left, giving
Indiana a chance to send the game into overtime.

	   But Penn State defended the play perfectly, forcing Eckart to
take an off-balance shot that bounced off the backboard as time
expired.
